	url = {http://www.jneurosci.org/cgi/content/abstract/29/43/13649},
	doi = {10.1523/JNEUROSCI.2672-09.2009},
	abstract = {The apical dendrite of layer 2/3 pyramidal cells in the piriform cortex receives two spatially distinct inputs: one projecting onto the distal apical dendrite in sensory layer 1a, the other targeting the proximal apical dendrite in layer 1b. We observe an expression gradient of A-type K+ channels that weakens the backpropagating action potential-mediated depolarization in layer 1a compared with layer 1b. We find that the pairing of presynaptic and postsynaptic firing leads to significantly smaller Ca2+ signals in the distal dendritic spines in layer 1a compared with the proximal spines in layer 1b. The consequence is a selective failure to induce long-term potentiation ({LTP)} in layer 1a, which can be rescued by pharmacological enhancement of action potential backpropagation. In contrast, {LTP} induction by pairing presynaptic and postsynaptic firing is possible in layer 1b but requires bursting of the postsynaptic cell. This output mode strongly depends on the balance of excitation and inhibition in the piriform cortex. We show, on the single-spine level, how the plasticity of functionally distinct synapses is gated by the intrinsic electrical properties of piriform cortex layer 2 pyramidal cell dendrites and the cellular output mode.},
	number = {43},
	urldate = {2010-03-17},
	journal = {J. Neurosci.},
	author = {Johenning, Friedrich W. and Beed, Prateep S. and Trimbuch, Thorsten and Bendels, Michael H. K. and Winterer, Jochen and Schmitz, Dietmar},
	month = oct,
	year = {2009},
	pages = {13649--13661},
	annote = {Summary:
Layer 2 piriform cortex ({PC)} cells recieve 2 kinds of inputs on its layer 1 dendrites. Its most proximal inputs in layer 1a are from the main olfactory bulb ({MOB)} and more distal inputs onto layer 1b from other {PC} associational fibers.
These two kinds of inputs recieve differentially back propagating action potentials from the soma ({APs} backprop to 1b but not 1a). [This is an effect of the distal dendrites expressing more Kv4.2 ({IA} current) than proximal.] As a result, 1b inputs are available for plasticity via {LTP} whereas 1a synapses do not show {LTP.}
Therefore, sensory inputs do not show plasticity but associational inputs do show plasticity. This is concurrent with hippocampal {CA1} pyramidal cells which have a similar input scheme where entorhinal cortex inputs do not show plasticity but associational inputs from elsewhere in the hippocampus (like dentate gyrus and {CA3)} do show plasticitiy.
I wonder if this is a general scheme of cortical neurons which recieve both direct sensory input and associational input as well.}
